{"parse":{"title":"Folly (allegory)","pageid":18803726,"revid":794091088,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Folly</b> (<a href=\"/wiki/Latin_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Latin language\">Latin</a>: <i><span lang=\"la\">Moria</span></i>) was a common allegorical figure in <a href=\"/wiki/Medieval\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Medieval\">medieval</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Morality_plays\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Morality plays\">morality plays</a> and in <a href=\"/wiki/Allegorical\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Allegorical\">allegorical</a> artwork through the <a href=\"/wiki/Renaissance\" title=\"Renaissance\">Renaissance</a>.  The depiction is generally of a young man, often similar in appearance to a <a href=\"/wiki/Jester\" title=\"Jester\">jester</a> or the tarot card, <a href=\"/wiki/The_Fool_(tarot_card)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"The Fool (tarot card)\">The Fool</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  In contrast to the many obvious <a href=\"/wiki/Classical_antiquity\" title=\"Classical antiquity\">classical</a> allusions in such works, the depictions owe little to the Greek goddess <a href=\"/wiki/At%C3%AB\" title=\"At\u00eb\">At\u00eb</a>.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Giotto-_The_Seven_Vices_-_Foolishness.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Giotto-_The_Seven_Vices_-_Foolishness.JPG/220px-Giotto-_The_Seven_Vices_-_Foolishness.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"410\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Giotto-_The_Seven_Vices_-_Foolishness.JPG/330px-Giotto-_The_Seven_Vices_-_Foolishness.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Giotto-_The_Seven_Vices_-_Foolishness.JPG/440px-Giotto-_The_Seven_Vices_-_Foolishness.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"600\" data-file-height=\"1117\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Giotto-_The_Seven_Vices_-_Foolishness.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A standard medieval <a href=\"/wiki/Allegory\" title=\"Allegory\">allegory</a> of Folly, painted by <a href=\"/wiki/Giotto\" title=\"Giotto\">Giotto</a>.</div></div></div>\n<p>In drama, the character tempts the protagonist into foolish action, successfully or not.  In an allegorical painting, the figure may be counterpoised to Prudence, representing a choice, or alone, representing the unwisdom of the actors in the painting.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Folly_(allegory)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i><a href=\"/wiki/In_Praise_of_Folly\" title=\"In Praise of Folly\">In Praise of Folly</a></i> by <a href=\"/wiki/Desiderius_Erasmus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Desiderius Erasmus\">Desiderius Erasmus</a>.</li>\n<li><i><a href=\"/wiki/Venus,_Cupid,_Folly_and_Time\" title=\"Venus, Cupid, Folly and Time\">Venus, Cupid, Folly and Time</a>, allegorical painting by <a href=\"/wiki/Agnolo_Bronzino\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Agnolo Bronzino\">Agnolo Bronzino</a></i></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Folly_(allegory)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Mackay, Constance D'Arcy (1915). <i>Costumes and Scenery for Amateurs</i>. Henry Holt and Company. p.&#160;197.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Costumes+and+Scenery+for+Amateurs&amp;rft.pages=197&amp;rft.pub=Henry+Holt+and+Company&amp;rft.date=1915&amp;rft.aulast=Mackay&amp;rft.aufirst=Constance+D%27Arcy&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFolly+%28allegory%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Folly_(allegory)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><cite class=\"citation book\">ed. A.W. Ward, A.R. Waller, W.P. Trent, J. Erskine, S.P. Sherman, and C. Van Doren. \"Sir David Lyndsay\". <i>The Cambridge history of English and American literature: An encyclopedia in eighteen volumes</i>. <b>III</b>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Sir+David+Lyndsay&amp;rft.btitle=The+Cambridge+history+of+English+and+American+literature%3A+An+encyclopedia+in+eighteen+volumes&amp;rft.au=ed.+A.W.+Ward%2C+A.R.+Waller%2C+W.P.+Trent%2C+J.+Erskine%2C+S.P.+Sherman%2C+and+C.+Van+Doren&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFolly+%28allegory%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span><span class=\"citation-comment\" style=\"display:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em\">CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Multiple_names:_authors_list\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list\">link</a>) CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Extra_text:_authors_list\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Extra text: authors l